{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486568"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"138"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/138"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.02,0.42,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"138"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/138"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"138"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2571"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44566"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of worsening breathlessness and dry cough. His exercise tolerance has declined from walking unlimited distances to becoming breathless after 100 metres. He has a history of asthma treated with as-required salbutamol. He does not take any other regular medications. He is an ex-smoker with a 15 pack-year history and recently retired from working in construction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is clubbing of his fingers. Chest examination reveals reduced expansion and fine crepitations throughout both lung fields without wheeze. A chest X-ray shows reduced lung volumes with a diffuse reticulonodular pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchoscopy","CT-guided lung biopsy","Positron emission tomography scan","Contrast-enhanced computed tomography chest","Pulmonary function tests"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features suggestive of interstitial lung disease (ILD), specifically idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF). The combination of progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, finger clubbing, reduced chest expansion, and bibasal crepitations is characteristic. Risk factors include smoking history and occupational exposure to construction dust.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate initial investigation. They will demonstrate the pattern of lung disease (typically restrictive in ILD), quantify disease severity, and provide a baseline for monitoring progression. The tests typically show reduced lung volumes with preserved flow rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast-enhanced computed tomography chest\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred imaging modality for ILD. Instead, high-resolution CT without contrast is the imaging of choice, but this should follow pulmonary function testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E has limited diagnostic value in ILD and is typically reserved for cases where infection or malignancy needs to be excluded, or when bronchoalveolar lavage might aid diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided lung biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely necessary and carries significant risks. It is only considered when HRCT and clinical features are inconclusive, particularly in younger patients where alternative diagnoses are more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositron emission tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E has no established role in the initial investigation of ILD. It may occasionally be useful if malignancy needs to be excluded but is not part of the standard diagnostic pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary function tests showing a restrictive pattern are characteristic of interstitial lung disease","High-resolution CT chest without contrast is the imaging modality of choice for interstitial lung disease","Clinical features of interstitial lung disease include progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, reduced chest expansion, and bibasal crepitations"],"references":["Wallis A, Spinks K. The diagnosis and management of interstitial lung diseases. BMJ 2015; 350:h2072. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/350/bmj.h2072"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"138"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T10:50:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T10:50:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"138"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77160"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}}